  "prompt": "Why does bullet bikes produce different sound than other bike?",
  "response": "Bullet bikes, specifically Royal Enfield motorcycles, produce a distinctive sound due to several factors:\n\n1. Engine Design\n- Single-cylinder engine with long stroke\n- Large displacement (350cc or 500cc)\n- Long piston travel creates a unique thump-like sound\n\n2. Exhaust System\n- Longer, wider exhaust pipes\n- Less restrictive exhaust design\n- Allows more sound resonance\n- Contributes to the characteristic \"thump\" or \"thumping\" sound\n\n3. Mechanical Configuration\n- Slower engine RPM\n- Larger and heavier engine components\n- More mechanical movement and vibration\n\n4. Historical Factors\n- Original design based on British motorcycle technology\n- Maintained traditional engineering approach\n- Preserved classic mechanical sound signature\n\n5. Aftermarket Modifications\n- Many riders customize exhaust systems\n- Performance exhausts enhance sound characteristics\n- Deliberate sound tuning for enthusiasts\n\nThese factors combine to create the iconic, deep, and rhythmic sound that distinguishes Bullet bikes from other motorcycles. The sound is often described as a steady, heavy \"thump-thump\" that has become synonymous with Royal Enfield motorcycles.\n\nThe unique sound is part of the bike's heritage and appeal, attracting enthusiasts who appreciate its classic mechanical character.",
